<% content_for :title, "#{@post[:title]} | devopsellence blog" %>

<main class="page page-article">
  <header class="article-header">
    <p class="article-back"><%= link_to "&larr; Blog".html_safe, blog_path %></p>
    <p class="article-series-label"><%= @post[:series] %> &mdash; Part <%= @post[:part] %> of 7</p>
    <h1><%= @post[:title] %></h1>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <time><%= @post[:date].strftime("%B %-d, %Y") %></time>
      <span><%= @post[:reading_time] %></span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="article-body">

    <p>In most deployment platforms, when you set a secret, it ends up in the platform's database. Encrypted, hopefully. But still there &mdash; accessible to anyone with database access, included in backups, and visible to any code path that can query the secrets table.</p>

    <p>devopsellence takes a different approach. <strong>Secret values are stored in GCP Secret Manager, not in the control plane database.</strong> The database stores only metadata: the secret name, which service it belongs to, and a SHA256 digest for change detection. The actual value goes directly to Secret Manager and is fetched at runtime by agents &mdash; not through the control plane.</p>

    <h2>The write path</h2>

    <p>When you run <code>devopsellence secret set --service web --name SECRET_KEY_BASE --stdin</code>:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>The CLI sends the secret value to the control plane API.</li>
      <li>The control plane creates (or updates) a secret in GCP Secret Manager, named <code>env-{slug}-{service}-{name}</code>.</li>
      <li>It grants <code>roles/secretmanager.secretAccessor</code> to the environment's dedicated GCP service account.</li>
      <li>It records metadata in the database: <code>gcp_secret_name</code>, <code>value_sha256</code>, <code>access_grantee_email</code>, <code>access_verified_at</code>.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>The secret value passes through the control plane API during the write &mdash; this is unavoidable since the CLI needs an authenticated endpoint to submit secrets. But the value is written directly to Secret Manager. It is <strong>not stored in the control plane database</strong>. The database column for the secret holds a SHA256 digest (for detecting whether the value has changed), not the value itself.</p>

    <p>The IAM grant uses <code>roles/secretmanager.secretAccessor</code>, which allows reading secret versions but not modifying or deleting secrets. The control plane retries IAM propagation (up to 20 attempts) because GCP IAM changes can take seconds to propagate globally.</p>

    <h2>The runtime read path</h2>

    <p>This is where the architecture pays off. When an agent reconciles a new deployment, secret values come from Secret Manager, not from the control plane:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>The signed desired-state envelope (delivered via GCS, see <a href="<%= blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-2-deploy-delivery") %>">Part 2</a>) contains <code>secretRefs</code> &mdash; a mapping of environment variable names to <code>gsm://</code> URIs.</li>
      <li>The agent uses its Workload Identity credentials (see <a href="<%= blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-4-identity") %>">Part 4</a>) to call the Secret Manager API directly.</li>
      <li>Secret Manager returns the value. The agent decodes it and injects it into the container's environment.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">Secret reference in desired state</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>"secretRefs": {
  "SECRET_KEY_BASE": "gsm://projects/example-runtime-project/secrets/env-prod-web-SECRET_KEY_BASE/versions/latest",
  "DATABASE_URL": "gsm://projects/example-runtime-project/secrets/env-prod-web-DATABASE_URL/versions/latest"
}</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p><strong>The control plane is not in this path.</strong> The agent resolves <code>gsm://</code> URIs by calling Secret Manager directly. If the control plane is down, agents can still resolve secrets for deployments they've already received.</p>

    <h2>Per-environment isolation</h2>

    <p>Each environment gets a dedicated GCP service account, created automatically during environment provisioning (e.g., <code>eb{token}@{project}.iam.gserviceaccount.com</code>). Secret Manager IAM bindings grant access only to that specific service account.</p>

    <p>This means:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Environment A's agent <strong>cannot read</strong> Environment B's secrets, even within the same organization.</li>
      <li>Isolation is enforced by GCP IAM, not by application-level checks in the control plane. Even if the control plane has a bug that leaks secret references, the agent can't resolve them without the right IAM binding.</li>
      <li>Every secret access is logged in GCP Cloud Audit Logs automatically. You don't need to build audit logging &mdash; it's a native property of Secret Manager.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The control plane periodically re-verifies IAM bindings (1-day interval) to ensure access grants haven't drifted. If a binding is missing, it's re-applied automatically.</p>

    <h2>Change detection</h2>

    <p>The control plane stores a <code>value_sha256</code> digest for each secret. When you update a secret, the digest is compared &mdash; if the value hasn't changed, no new Secret Manager version is created. This avoids unnecessary version accumulation for idempotent operations (like re-running a CI pipeline that sets the same secrets every deploy).</p>

    <h2>What this gives you</h2>

    <p>Compared to storing secrets in the control plane database:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>No secret values in the database.</strong> A database compromise, backup leak, or SQL injection doesn't expose secret values.</li>
      <li><strong>Per-environment IAM isolation.</strong> Access is enforced by GCP, not application code.</li>
      <li><strong>Automatic audit trail.</strong> Cloud Audit Logs for every access, no custom implementation.</li>
      <li><strong>Automatic encryption and key rotation.</strong> Google-managed encryption at rest, with optional CMEK for customer-managed keys.</li>
      <li><strong>Version history.</strong> Secret Manager maintains automatic version history. Rollbacks are a Secret Manager operation.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Next: <strong><%= link_to "Part 4 — Zero-credential nodes with Workload Identity Federation", blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-4-identity") %></strong></p>

  </article>

  <%= render "marketing/blog/series_nav" %>
</main>
